All 54 test cases pass against the DEV Session 4 implementation (maybe_sudo() fix).

## Summary

### What was tested
DEV Session 4 added `maybe_sudo()` helper to `setup.sh` to fix a regression where
`install_dep()` hardcoded `sudo` for apt/dnf/yum commands. In containers running
without `sudo` (uid != 0), this caused setup.sh to fail at `gh` auto-install.

### Test results
- TC-01..TC-51 (existing suite): 51/51 PASS — no regressions
- TC-52..TC-54 (new: maybe_sudo coverage): 3/3 PASS

### New tests added
- TC-52: maybe_sudo() helper function exists in setup.sh
- TC-53: install_dep() uses maybe_sudo (not hardcoded sudo) for apt/dnf/yum
- TC-54: maybe_sudo() has both root-check and sudo-check branches

### Requirement coverage
All acceptance criteria from REQUIREMENT.md §2.1–§2.9 and §5.1 remain covered.
The Session 4 fix satisfies the implicit requirement that setup.sh must not require
elevated privileges (§3.5) in container environments running without sudo.

### Test environment note
`gh` CLI must be pre-installed (or downloadable via curl to ~/bin) before running
setup.sh in a sudo-less container. The test harness sets PATH="${HOME}/bin:${PATH}"
to pick up a manually bootstrapped binary. This is an expected pre-condition for the
test environment; real end-user machines have package manager access.
